description: Pullman Radio News Palouse Area Robotics team fares well at World Championship  May 3, 2016 Evan Ellis News  The Palouse Area Robotics team the Sciborgs fared well at last weekend’s World Championship in Saint Louis.  The team made up of high school students from both sides of the state line made it into the finals of their field which included 75 teams. description: Pullman Radio News WSU Pullman campus construction projects on Regents agenda this week  November 15, 2017 Evan Ellis News       The Washington State University Regents are set to deal with new construction projects during their monthly meeting this week.  Designs for 2 new research buildings in Pullman will be considered for approval.  The Global Animal Health Phase 2 building is slated to be an addition to the Allen Center.  The facility would be the new home for the Paul Allen School for Globa ... l Animal Health disease detection and surveillance program.  The building near the Veterinary Hospital will house research and development labs.        The regents will also consider approving final design of the next facility in the research complex on Stadium Way.  The Plant Sciences Building 5 is slated to be built just North of Johnson Hall where a parking lot is currently located.  The designs will be considered in committee Thursday before the WSU Regents consider approval Friday.        The Institutional Infrastructure Committee is scheduled to hear a verbal update on previously approved real estate transactions. Crystle Morgan and Bruce Kenoyer both have 53 votes.  They were tied on election night before Morgan took a one vote lead late last week.  In Pullman Dan Records leads Garren Shannon by 3 votes for city council.  Records lead was at 10 votes after the last round of tabulation.  In Uniontown Ray Hei ... tstuman now leads Steve Kelly for a town council seat by one vote.  The men were tied at the last count on Thursday.  Jason Fletcher leads Alyssa Heagy by 3 votes in Tekoa for city council.  And in Rosalia Bob Hill leads Janet Strohl by 4 votes for city council.  None of the other contested race leaders have changed from election night. The Farmington street levy is still being rejected after barely passing on election night.  All other small taxing district levies in Whitman County are continuing to pass.  The Whitman County Auditor’s Office still has about 500 ballots left to count. description: Pullman Radio News Pullman voters approve bond to relocate city hall  November 14, 2017 Evan Ellis News  Pullman voters have approved the large bond to relocate city hall.  The Whitman County Auditor’s Office counted another roughly 600 vote by mail ballots from last week’s election today.  That brought the number of ballots from the City of Pullman to about 3,900 which is enough to validate the vote.  Proposition 1 has passed with 63% approval.  The 10.5 million dollar bond will be used primaril ... y to relocate city hall to the Encounter Ministries campus on Pioneer Hill.  Other funds from the bond will purchase land for a 3rd fire station and provide full funding for the long planned for Lawson Gardens House.  The validation also means that prop 2 has passed.  The 2.4 million dollar bond will be spent on park and path improvements.  That issue has passed with 73% of the vote.  There are still about 500 ballots countywide left to tabulate.  The Auditor’s Office will run another batch on Thursday.   See More

description: Peter Hire So. Rogue One. First off, it's a pretty good movie. I preferred The Force Awakens, but again, this was good. Not quite my favorite this year, Doctor Strange holds that title so far, but I haven't seen Moana yet. HOWEVER. To quote  Kenji  after Force Awakens last year, "I have some problems."  Aside from the Star Wars canon issues (to echo  Chris D - RIP Kyle Katarn, 1995-2016), which I can mostly deal with, there's a few plot issues, particularly what happens at the very end. No spoilers. My two big beefs though- the movie uses some cliches that frequently make me facepalm- again, can't go into into it without spoilers- and while the characters were likable enough, there wasn't enough time to build up a connection with so many of them. And once again, I can't go into more detail without entering major spoiler territory.   The movie did a few other things well- it definitely feels like Star Wars, Darth Vader is as badass as ever, and the production team did an amazing job digitally inserting Peter Cushing (as Tarkin, you may recall him from A New Hope) into the movie- you could tell he was computer generated, but he fit much better than CBS's budget job of digitally inserting Jack Lord into the season premiere of Hawaii Five-0 a couple months ago (points if you understand what the hell I'm even talking about).   Overall, a good movie, with some issues, and a decent addition to the Star Wars universe.

description: Chris Sheridan  is with  Bonnie Sheridan  and  Joe Sheridan . It's about 2 years since I announced I'd be leaving SEL. Since then... a lot has changed. I think I've grown more in these 2 years through the choices I made than I would have had I remained at SEL. Even with how much people like  Grant ,  Kenji ,  Carrie ,  Huma , and  Ahsan  could have taught me it's nothing compared to how far out of my comfort zone I went, and what I learned while out of my comfort zone.  Now, I have true confidence in that I know how to test things. With a sample size of 1 company and 1 development group it was hard to extrapolate a strong confidence from the small sample. Now I've worked at 3 companies, with everything from any resource I wanted to half a desk and a laptop. Each challenge I've been dropped in to I've received the feedback of that not only do I do the job well, but I push others to do the job well.  I still miss my friends at SEL, I miss the friends I made at IdentityMind ( Derek  is the only one I can tag), and I miss having my family just an hour (or less) away. Always wondering (at least a little) if the people that I trained have continued to excel or if that's just something I tell myself to erase doubt in my choices.  As I take a moment to look back, I know that I've made some lifelong friendships, even if they just stay on Facebook, and when the question is asked "Was it worth it?" I can answer confidently that as I turn to the future the answer is yes.  I'm looking forward to this next year at Gogo where I will continue to push myself, and those around me to ensure we release the best damn products possible. Just like before, I will also make new friends like  Amanda  while I'm at Gogo.  So, this is just a quick moment to thank my friends and co-workers from the past, and the future. You have all made work fun. Also thank you Mom & Dad for supporting me in my move away from the Inland Northwest. This would have been much harder emotionally without that support.  In case anyone's wondering, I am perfectly okay. I just tend to get a bit more retrospective between Matt's birthday and my own. Especially with each May recently having a surprise announcement of a new job (don't worry Gogo, I'm sticking around). Work and home were a little to busy to process things, and it's all coming out in this novel of a post. (Congrats if you read all the way to here.)

description: Pullman Chamber Schweitzer Engineering Laboratories  SEL donates $150k to American Red Cross, discounts products for customers affected by Harvey  PULLMAN, Wash. — August 29, 2017 — Schweitzer Engineering Laboratories has donated $150,000 to the American Red Cross for Hurricane Harvey relief efforts. The company is also offering customers a price reduction, and expedited shipping, for products bound for the affected areas.  “Our employees, customers, and the communities impacted by this hurricane are in our thoughts and prayers,” said SEL President Edmund O. Schweitzer, III, who, along with his wife Beatriz, made a $100,000 personal donation to the American Red Cross.  SEL has five branch offices in Texas, with 52 employees in Houston. The company also has sales representatives and numerous customer in the affected region.  “Our customers in the electric power industry really go above and beyond in times of need, working under the most difficult circumstances and often sending their personnel into harms' way to get the lights back on,” said David Costello, VP of Sales and Customer Services, who works out of SEL’s office in Fair Oaks Ranch, Texas. “We are proud to do our part by making it easier for them to get the products they need by cutting the prices, expediting deliveries, and mobilizing employees to be on call for technical support.”  Customers can reach SEL technical support, call 509.338.3838.  SEL serves the power industry worldwide through the design, manufacture, supply and support of products and services for power system protection, monitoring, control, automation, communications and metering. For more than 30 years, SEL has offered unmatched local technical support, a 10-year worldwide product warranty and a commitment to making electric power safer, more reliable and more economical. Tim
